Bellman ford algorithm
In a graph with V vertices the longest graph can have V-1 edges
A simple path means
1.No repeated vertices
2.No cycles.
In the first iteration
The outer loop represents the number of times we relax edges
i=0 at most 1 edge
i=1 at most 2 edges
i=v-2 at most v-1 edges
The inner jth loop represnts the number of edges
suppose 
0 to 1 (5)
1 to 2 (3)
2 to 3 (2)
First outer loop i=0
Now we are going through all edges
0 to 1 (update dist[1]=5)
1 to 2 (not updated because dist[1] was infinity at start.
why second iteration?
because shortest path distance algorithm may not fully propagate in the fisrt iteration due to edge ordering.

